Lastly, Pattinson always was injury prone, my vote is for Neser & Siddle, ergo youth & experience.

snippet.textDisplay: The pitch had excessive bounce and lateral movement, batting first was a lottery for Australia. It got bad from late day 2. Australia lasted just as long in their second innings as NZ, batsmen from both side hoping around. The result could have been the other way if NZ batted first. NZ bowlers bowling around 130kmh looked deadly in the second innings let alone someone like Mitchell Starc and Cummins who bowl around 140-145kmh. That was always going to be a challenge for NZ. I don't like day/night test cricket, not a pitch like Perth, unfair disadvantage for the team batting under light if you don't have a bit of luck. Someone will be killed with this pink ball under lights, we do not want an incident like Hughes, ICC need to stick with the traditions of the game. It was just a mockery of test cricket.

NZ bowlers bowling around 130kmh looked deadly in the second innings let alone someone like Mitchell Starc and Cummins who bowl around 140-145kmh. That was always going to be a challenge for NZ. I don't like day/night test cricket, not a pitch like Perth, unfair disadvantage for the team batting under light if you don't have a bit of luck. Someone will be killed with this pink ball under lights, we do not want an incident like Hughes, ICC need to stick with the traditions of the game. It was just a mockery of test cricket.

snippet.textDisplay: Straylians keep saying NZ is 2nd best team, but my understanding is that after Australia beat Pakistan they went to 2nd and NZ to third in the ratings. It was a pink ball test, which NZ hasn't played in a looong time, especially not under lights, and especially not in 38 degree heat day after day. First test in Aus is always an ambush, and visiting team has to win the toss to have any chance (and take every catch/runout chance).
